<statement>
<p>Solve this system of equations using elimination.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{9}{x}+{3}{y}={60}</m> </p>
<p>
  <m>\displaystyle{7}{x}+{4}{y}={60}</m></p>
<p><fillin characters="8" /></p>

</statement>
<solution>
<p><ul><li><m>\displaystyle{\left({4},{8}\right)}</m></li></ul></p><p>We chose (for no special reason) to use the first equation to eliminate x from the second equation.</p>
<p>To eliminate we need the scaled version of equation one to have a coefficient of -7. So we scale by <m>\displaystyle-\frac{{7}}{{9}}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-\frac{{{7}}}{{9}}{\left({9}{x}+{3}{y}\right)}=-\frac{{{7}}}{{9}}{\left({60}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle-{\left({7}\right)}{x}+-{2.3333333333333}{y}=-{46.666666666667}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{7}{x}+{4}{y}={60}</m></p>
<p>Adding these two equations gives us</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{1.6666666666667}{y}={13.333333333333}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}=\frac{{13.333333333333}}{{1.6666666666667}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{y}={8}</m></p>
<p>Finally we can substitute this y value into the first equation to solve for x.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{9}{x}+{3}{\left({8}\right)}={60}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{9}{x}+{\left({24}\right)}={60}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{9}{x}={60}-{\left({24}\right)}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{9}{x}={36}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}=\frac{{36}}{{9}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{x}={4}</m></p>
<p>Thus the answer is <m>\displaystyle{\left({4},{8}\right)}</m>.</p>

</solution>
</myopenmath>

